body: Hi Kudo, I'm sorry for this difficulty. I'm not able to reproduce your problem (I'm using XCode 7.1 too); building gives me just warnings that are being worked on: To help me debug the issue, could you tell me what's the diagnostic information given by XCode when you open any of the errors shown (by clicking the triangle)? Also, to double check, after you do `pod install`, the workspace created should have these folders and products: Is that what you have? Cheers, Jorge

Hi, Jorge

Thanks for your comment. In fact, I got other compile error at the beginning, you can see it in this picture.
![git](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4947330/10961646/f2d6067c-83cb-11e5-8007-96164e149bb7.png)

It seems that the compiler doesn't find the definition of `time_t`, so I include a header file by adding `#include <sys/time.h>` below the line `#include <time.h>` in "/include/grpc/support/time.h". I build it again and I get the errors like I described in the issue. Please see my pictures.

![git2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4947330/10961910/621ce9ea-83ce-11e5-8c03-e7b81d7a53c7.png)

![git3](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4947330/10961913/6d980890-83ce-11e5-8b3d-7303cc2067ac.png)

![git4](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4947330/10961936/a5134d84-83ce-11e5-9fb7-6d4ee6fcf2cf.png)

Hi, Jorge

I think I have mess the project up so I removed the `grpc` directory and redo the whole process. If I build with my iPhone6(real device), everything goes well except for a link error which is about Bitcode. After I disable the Bitcode in `RouteGuideClient` Build settings, build success. But it only works on real device, if I switch to simulator for example iPhone 6s, I get the error again.

![git5](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4947330/10962585/5ae24048-83d4-11e5-99f6-bc27334ba607.png)

Thanks for your time.

The problem XCode 7 has with `time.h` should have gone away on the master branch after PR https://github.com/grpc/grpc/pull/3990 (and on the release 0.11 branch after PR https://github.com/grpc/grpc/pull/4011). Can you verify that you're checked out past that commit?

My Podfile is

>  pod 'Protobuf', '~> 3.0.0-alpha-4'
>  pod 'gRPC', '~> 0.11.1'

It shows :

> Installing OpenSSL (1.0.204.1)
> Installing Protobuf (3.0.0-alpha-4.1)
> Installing gRPC (0.11.1)

I created another Project and pod install again. Now the errors have gone, thanks Jorge : )
No problem! Please let us know how the library works for you!
Yes, I will do after using it for some time.

I'm also experiencing this issue when running on a device, but _not_ when running through simulator. Picture of build errors: And the podspec which generates the client: ``` Pod::Spec.new do |s| s.name = 'octopus' s.version = '0.0.1' s.license = '...' s.ios.deployment_target = '7.1' s.osx.deployment_target = '10.9' # Run protoc with the Objective-C and gRPC plugins to generate protocol messages and gRPC clients. # You can run this command manually if you later change your protos and need to regenerate. s.prepare_command = "protoc --objc_out=. --objcgrpc_out=. --proto_path=../../../proto ../../../proto/*.proto" # The --objc_out plugin generates a pair of .pbobjc.h/.pbobjc.m files for each .proto file. s.subspec "Messages" do |ms| ms.source_files = "*.pbobjc.{h,m}" ms.header_mappings_dir = "." ms.requires_arc = false ms.dependency "Protobuf", "~> 3.0.0-alpha-4" end # The --objcgrpc_out plugin generates a pair of .pbrpc.h/.pbrpc.m files for each .proto file with # a service defined. s.subspec "Services" do |ss| ss.source_files = "*.pbrpc.{h,m}" ss.header_mappings_dir = "." ss.requires_arc = true ss.dependency "gRPC", "~> 0.12" ss.dependency "#{s.name}/Messages" end end ``` @jcanizales Any way to triage this? I tried deleting the `Pods` and running `pod install`, this didn't achieve anything for me. I believe I am up to date on the `gRPC` and `protobuf` deps.
Is there a way for either of you guys to share a project with us, to reproduce this issue? It's so weird that I'm afraid there's not much I can do if I can't actually look at it.

After trying to reproduce the issue, I've found that it's probably just something with my configuration for my pods that are used in the debug scheme because I couldn't create the error in a new project. If I switch the debug scheme to use the release pods, the simulator runs fine, but I can't push it to a real device without the error occuring. Any ideas?
